This paper is about generative models, specifically Flow-GANs, which combine maximum likelihood and adversarial learning. The paper uses MNIST and CIFAR-10 datasets for experiments, which are commonly used in computer vision research. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the paper uses neural networks for training, which falls under cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category. Finally, the paper also discusses the evaluation of likelihood scores, which is related to cs.SD (Sound).
